stylometry: Determining the total cost of manaing a product in inventory deals with having enough inventory on hand vs. the cost of ordering. The company does not want to run out of products that customers demand. There is also a fixed cost incurred every time a company orders from their supplier. Plus, there is a holding cost and interest cost of tying up money in inventory. We must determine how much to order and when to order. How much to order deals with the economic order quanitity (EOQ). In the EOQ equation, no stockouts are allowed and unit cost is constant, with no quanitiy discounts. The total cost is the annual carrying cost plus the annual ordering cost. The carrying costs are equal to the quanitity divided by 2, times the cost of holding. Ordering costs are equal to demand divided by order size, times demand. Reorder point (ROP) is the other formula. It understands the affects of running out of inventory. The more negative effect on shortages, the higher the ROP and level of safety stock. ROP = expected demand during lead time + std dev during lead time (decision variable). The std dev during lead time times the decision varible equals the level of safety stock.
